I think I've found the cause of this. In <pcre.h> from pcre 8.37, the entry points for pcre are defined as:

PCRE_EXP_DECL void _(_pcre_malloc)(size_t);
void  (_pcre_free)(void *);
PCRE_EXP_DECL void *(_pcre_stack_malloc)(size_t);
PCRE_EXP_DECL void  (*pcre_stack_free)(void *);
etc.
PCRE_EXP_DECL gets expanded to "extern "c"".  

Multiple programs in RE2 directly or indirectly include "util/pcre.h" which includes <pcre.h>. and thus define pcre_free. Without an "extern" declaration, the MSVC linker doesn't like this. 

I consider this a bug in pcre 8.37; pcre_free should be defined with PCRE_EXP_DECL, same as the other PCRE entry points. If I make this correction and rebuild pcre.lib, the programs using pcre link okay in RE2.

We have an easy workaround.  Do not include <pcre.h> in "util/pcre.h". Instead, include it in pcre.cpp, which is the only program that calls the pcre C functions.

